This project is a practical exercise to strengthen my understanding of OOP and clean software architecture.  
My main focus was implementing a maintainable, layered MVC-style architecture using vanilla JS, HTML and CSS.  
In the beginning I mixed UI-, controller- and model-logic, because what I learned in class was closer to an MVP pattern.  
Over time I refactored the code into a clean MVC structure to clearly separate concerns.

Technically, this project applies multiple core software engineering principles:
– OOP with encapsulated models and private fields  
– constructor-based dependency injection  
– a layered MVC-style architecture  
– asynchronous JavaScript with multi-layer async flow  
– template-based rendering without frameworks  
– REST API integration through a custom Express proxy  
– separation of concerns between View, Controller, Model and Service  
– structured error handling and validation  


┌───────────────────────────────┐
│           Frontend             │
└───────────────────────────────┘

          User Input
               │
               ▼
        ┌──────────────┐
        │     View      │
        │ (UI Renderer) │
        └──────────────┘
               │ events
               ▼
        ┌──────────────┐
        │  Controller   │
        │  (App Logic)  │
        └──────────────┘
          │         │
   update │         │ fetch data
          ▼         ▼
   ┌──────────────┐  ┌──────────────┐
   │    Model      │  │   Service    │
   │ (Data Layer)  │  │ (API Client) │
   └──────────────┘  └──────────────┘
                           │ HTTP
                           ▼
                ┌────────────────────┐
                │    Backend API     │
                │   (Express Proxy)  │
                └────────────────────┘
                           │ fetch
                           ▼
                ┌────────────────────┐
                │  OpenLibrary API    │
                └────────────────────┘


At this time, the implementation of the data handling for the OpenLibrary API response is still missing and will be added later.
